title: LCQ2: Designated poultry zones in markets
secretary_name: Secretary for the Environment and Food, Mrs Lily Yam
question_text: Following is a question by the Hon.Tommy Cheung and a reply by the Secretary for the Environment and Food, Mrs Lily Yam, in the Legislative Council meeting today (December 19): Question It is learnt that after terminating the tenancy of a live chicken retail stall, the Food and Environmental Hygiene Department (FEHD) will not let out the stall again for the same business purpose. In this connection, will the Government inform this Council: (a)	when FEHD started to implement the above-mentioned policy, the number of stalls involved so far, and whether the purpose of the policy is to eradicate stalls selling live

number of stalls involved so far, and whether the purpose of the policy is to eradicate stalls selling live chickens; (b)	whether the Hong Kong Housing Authority and the Hong Kong Housing Society have implemented the same policy for live chicken stalls under their management; and (c)	whether the Hong Kong Housing Authority, Hong Kong Housing Society and FEHD  have implemented the same policy to stalls selling other types of fresh meat, seafood and vegetables under their management?
reply_text: (a) Since its establishment, the Food and Environmental Hygiene Department (FEHD) has been committed to stepping up market management and improving the environmental hygiene and ventilation  systems of wet markets.  On the management of vacant stalls (including live poultry stalls), the FEHD will, generally, in light of the situation of individual markets, consider the following factors before deciding on whether or not to offer the vacant stalls for public auction : (1) the number of stalls selling the same type of commodities and the overall business environment of the market; (2) the need for reserving vacant stalls for reprovisioning other stallholders affected by market

(2) the need for reserving vacant stalls for reprovisioning other stallholders affected by market demolition or market improvement works; and (3) the need for making use of vacant stalls to cope with market improvement works such as widening of passageway and extension of the size of individual stalls. As regards poultry stalls, apart from the above considerations, FEHD's target is to establish designated poultry zones to separate poultry stalls from other types of stalls. This measure was introduced after the 1997 Avian Flu incident and implemented since June last year. This measure would not only improve the environmental hygiene of poultry stalls and reduce the

since June last year. This measure would not only improve the environmental hygiene of poultry stalls and reduce the over-crowding therein, but would also facilitate the installation of separate ventilation system for poultry stalls. Therefore, whenever live poultry stalls or stalls in the vicinity of poultry stalls are vacated, these stalls will not be immediately put forward for public auction. Up to now, 72 poultry stalls and 33 stalls of other types have remained vacant for the purpose of establishing designated poultry zones. (b)The maximum number of poultry stalls in markets managed by the Hong Kong Housing Authority (HA) and the Hong Kong Housing Society (HS) is

managed by the Hong Kong Housing Authority (HA) and the Hong Kong Housing Society (HS) is eight and two respectively. By contrast, there is a maximum of 36 poultry stalls in one single FEHD market, which is a far greater number than that in HA or HS markets.  Besides, the average size of individual poultry stalls in markets managed by HA  is bigger. The average area of a poultry stall in an HA market is about 25 m2 while that of a poultry stall in an FEHD market is 20.2 m2.  As such, our priority is to improve the overcrowding situation of poultry

m2.  As such, our priority is to improve the overcrowding situation of poultry stalls managed by FEHD and to gradually separate them from other stalls.  In parallel, we have started discussion with the Housing Department to explore whether the same measure should be introduced in HA markets.  The final decision will be made by HA. As regards markets managed by the HS, there are a total of four poultry stalls in three markets hence there is no need for setting up designated poultry zones. (c)The above-mentioned measure applies only to poultry stalls and is not applicable to other stalls in FEHD, HA and HS markets.
